 piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":9,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":29,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":39,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":49,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret De Salmesbury was born in 1057, in Hindley, Lancashire, England. She married Leofwin De Hindley I. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1109, in her hometown."},"et":{"1057–after 1109":"1057–pärast 1109","1058–1106":"1058–1106","1100–1150":"1100–1150","1057–1109":"1057–1109","1106":"1106","after 1109":"pärast 1109","1058":"1058","1057":"1057","Abt 1100":"umbes 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1109":"1109","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1057–after 1109":"1057–1109 jälkeen","1058–1106":"1058–1106","1100–1150":"1100–1150","1057–1109":"1057–1109","1106":"1106","after 1109":"1109 jälkeen","1058":"1058","1057":"1057","Abt 1100":"noin 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1109":"1109","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1057–after 1109":"1057–après 1109","1058–1106":"1058–1106","1100–1150":"1100–1150","1057–1109":"1057–1109","1106":"1106","after 1109":"après 1109","1058":"1058","1057":"1057","Abt 1100":"environ 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1109":"1109","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret De Salmesbury est née en 1057, à Hindley, Lancashire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé Leofwin De Hindley I. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée après 1109, dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1057–after 1109":"1057–nach 1109","1058–1106":"1058–1106","1100–1150":"1100–1150","1057–1109":"1057–1109","1106":"1106","after 1109":"nach 1109","1058":"1058","1057":"1057","Abt 1100":"um 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1109":"1109","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, England","lifeSummary":"Margaret De Salmesbury wur